* #### Call to reduce sugar in sugar-sweetened drinks
A new study, published in The Lancet Diabetes & Endocrinology journal,
suggests that reducing sugar content in sugar sweetened drinks in the UK by 40
per cent over five years, without replacing them with any artificial
sweeteners, could prevent 500,000 cases of overweight and one million cases of
obesity, in turn preventing around 300,000 cases of Type 2 diabetes, over two
decades.A new study, published in The Lancet Diabetes & Endocrinology journal,
suggests that reducing sugar content in sugar sweetened drinks in the UK by 40
per cent over five years, without replacing them with any artificial
sweeteners, could prevent 500,000 cases of overweight and one million cases of
obesity, in turn preventing around 300,000 cases of Type 2 diabetes, over two
* #### New 'Sugar smart' app launched 
Parents are being encouraged to sign up for a free app which tells them the
sugar content of food and drink. The new 'Sugar Smart' app from Public Health
England works by scanning the barcode of products to show the total sugar
content in cubes or grams, aiming to help parents take control of their
children’s sugar intake.Parents are being encouraged to sign up for a free app
